  "title": "‘Captain Marvel’ Is a ’90s Nostalgia Play. Did It Work? | Exit Survey",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2019-03-08",
  "runtimeMin": 64,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins exit-survey the MCU's first female-led movie, weighing its overstuffed origin story and BuzzFeed-listicle ’90s needle-drops against the Wonder Woman it can't quite match.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The ‘Captain Marvel’ Exit Survey",
      "note": "spoilers throughout",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Captain Marvel",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Brie Larson's Carol Danvers, judged as a movie asked to do five jobs at once: an origin story, a S.H.I.E.L.D. prequel, the Kree-Skrull war, an Avengers setup, and a ’90s period piece. Fennessey calls the storytelling rickety and the girl-power framing reactive; Dobbins finds it functional but forgettable. Both snag on the needle-drops (No Doubt's 'Just a Girl' over the big fight, Nirvana's 'Come as You Are') as a Happy Meal version of the decade. Larson comes alive only riffing with Samuel L. Jackson; Ben Mendelsohn's Talos is the film's real emotional center."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wonder Woman",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "The bar Dobbins keeps returning to: origin dispatched in the first 30 minutes, its heroine a god instead of a real person, an underdog where Captain Marvel is a corporate sure thing."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
